🎙️ Adaptive Noise-Robust Offline Voice-Controlled Microcontroller using TinyML

📌 Project Overview

This project presents an Adaptive Noise-Robust Offline Voice-Controlled Microcontroller System implemented using TinyML, ESP32, and Edge Impulse.

The system performs offline keyword recognition directly on embedded hardware without requiring:

Internet connectivity
Cloud processing

External servers

The project is specifically designed to provide:

✅ Real-Time Voice Recognition

✅ Privacy-Preserving Operation

✅ Low Power Consumption

✅ Noise-Robust Performance

✅ Embedded Edge AI Inference

Audio captured using the INMP441 I2S digital microphone undergoes multiple stages of intelligent signal processing including:

Adaptive Noise Filtering

Voice Activity Detection (VAD)

MFCC Feature Extraction

TinyML Keyword Spotting

The trained TinyML model deployed on the ESP32 identifies predefined keywords locally. When the target command "RED" is detected with sufficient confidence, the ESP32 activates connected outputs such as:

💡 LEDs

⚡ Relay Modules

📟 OLED Display Feedback

This project demonstrates the practical deployment of intelligent voice interfaces on low-resource embedded systems while maintaining high efficiency, low latency, and enhanced privacy.

✨ Key Features

Offline Voice Recognition

TinyML-Based Keyword Spotting

Real-Time Embedded Inference

Adaptive Noise Filtering

Voice Activity Detection (VAD)
 
MFCC Feature Extraction

OLED Display Integration

LED / Relay Control

Privacy-Preserving AI

Low-Power Embedded Operation

Cloud-Free Processing

Scalable Multi-Command Architecture

Project Objectives

The primary objectives of this project are:

Develop an offline voice recognition system using TinyML.

Implement keyword spotting directly on ESP32 hardware.

Improve recognition reliability under noisy environmental conditions.

Reduce dependence on cloud-based speech recognition systems.

Provide a low-latency and privacy-focused embedded AI solution.

Demonstrate real-time embedded inference using Edge Impulse.

Create a scalable framework for future multi-command voice control systems.

🏗️ System Architecture

Processing Pipeline

Microphone Input
        ↓
Adaptive Noise Filtering
        ↓
Voice Activity Detection (VAD)
        ↓
MFCC Feature Extraction
        ↓
TinyML Inference
        ↓
ESP32 Decision Logic
        ↓
LED / Relay Output

🧩 Description of Block Diagram

![Block Diagram](Docs/Block Diagram.png)

🎤 1. Microphone Input

The INMP441 I2S digital microphone captures environmental audio signals and sends digital audio samples to the ESP32 for processing.

Functions

Real-time audio acquisition

Continuous voice monitoring

Digital audio communication through I2S protocol

🔇 2. Adaptive Noise Filtering

The system dynamically estimates ambient environmental noise levels and adjusts filtering thresholds accordingly.

Advantages :

Improves speech clarity

Enhances recognition reliability

Maintains performance in noisy surroundings

🎙️ 3. Voice Activity Detection (VAD)

Voice Activity Detection identifies valid speech frames while eliminating silence and irrelevant background noise.

Benefits:

Reduces unnecessary processing

Lowers power consumption

Improves TinyML inference efficiency

📊 4. MFCC Feature Extraction

MFCC (Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients) converts speech audio into compact numerical feature representations suitable for machine learning.

Purpose:

Preserves critical speech characteristics

Reduces dimensionality

Improves classification accuracy

🧠 5. TinyML Inference

Extracted MFCC features are passed into the TinyML keyword spotting model trained using Edge Impulse.

Classification Labels

noise

red

unknown

Inference Characteristics

✅ Embedded Execution

✅ Real-Time Processing

✅ Offline Operation

✅ Low Latency

⚙️ 6. ESP32 Decision Logic

The ESP32 evaluates the prediction confidence scores generated by the TinyML model.

Decision Condition

If:

Confidence("RED") > Threshold

Then:

✅ Output Device Activated

💡 7. Output Module

The system activates connected peripherals when the target keyword is detected.

Output Devices

LEDs

Relay Modules

Motors

OLED Display Feedback

🔌 Circuit Description

![Circuit Diagram](Hardware/block.png)

The ESP32 acts as the central processing unit of the system.

🎤 INMP441 Microphone Connections

  | INMP441 Pin | ESP32 Connection |
| ----------- | ---------------- |
| VDD         | 3.3V             |
| GND         | GND              |
| WS          | GPIO25           |
| SCK         | GPIO27           |
| SD          | GPIO33           |

📟 OLED Display Connections

The SSD1306 OLED communicates using the I2C protocol

| OLED Pin | ESP32 Connection |
| -------- | ---------------- |
| VCC      | 3.3V / 5V        |
| GND      | GND              |
| SCL      | GPIO22           |
| SDA      | GPIO21           |

💡 Output Device Connections

LEDs or relay modules are connected to ESP32 GPIO pins and are activated upon successful keyword detection.

🔋 Power Supply

The complete system is powered using:

5V USB Supply

Battery Source

🛠️ Hardware Components

The prototype consists of:

ESP32 Development Board

INMP441 Digital Microphone

SSD1306 OLED Display

Relay Module / LEDs

Breadboard

Jumper Wires

🧠 Model Description

The TinyML model was trained using Edge Impulse for embedded keyword spotting applications.

📊 Feature Extraction Technique

The model uses:

MFCC (Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients)

MFCC converts speech waveforms into compact feature vectors while preserving important speech characteristics.

Advantages

✅ Compact Representation

✅ Noise Robustness

✅ Efficient Embedded Processing

✅ Improved Speech Classification

🏷️ Classification Labels

The TinyML model classifies audio into:

noise

red

unknown

🚀 Deployment Platform

The trained model is deployed directly on ESP32 using:

Edge Impulse Deployment Libraries

TensorFlow Lite Micro

📈 Model Performance

| Metric             | Value |
| ------------------ | ----- |
| Accuracy           | 96.8% |
| Weighted Precision | 0.97  |
| Weighted Recall    | 0.97  |
| Weighted F1 Score  | 0.97  |
| ROC AUC            | 0.98  |

📊 Performance Analysis

The model achieved high recognition accuracy under normal environmental conditions.

Adaptive noise thresholding improved:

✅ Target keyword detection

✅ Background noise rejection

✅ Unknown speech handling

The confusion matrix indicates reliable classification performance across all predefined classes.

